TEXT(&beginproblem);
$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;
$a=random(1,10,1)*random(-1,1,2);
$b=random(1,10,1)*random(-1,1,2);
$c=random(1,10,1)*random(-1,1,2);

BEGIN_TEXT

$PAR
If the curve \(y=f(x),\;a \le x \le b,\) is rotated about the horizontal line \(y=c,\) where \(f(x) \le c,\) then one can prove that a formula for the area of the resulting surface is
\[S = \int_{a}^{\,b} {2\pi [c-f(x)] \sqrt{1+[f'(x)]^2}}\, dx.\]
Use this formula and a computer algebra system to find the area of the surface generated by rotating the curve \(y=\sqrt{x},\; 0 \le x \le 4,\) about the line \(y=4.\) 

$PAR
Surface area = \{ans_rule(45)\}

END_TEXT

ANS(num_cmp("31/6*pi*17^(1/2)+1/2*pi*4^(1/2)*ln(33+8*17^(1/2))+1/6*pi"));

